<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">41506716</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2026</Year><Month>02</Month><Day>01</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>02</Month><Day>01</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1449-8987</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>23</Volume><Issue>1</Issue><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Feb</Month><Day>05</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Sexual health</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Sex Health</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Dialectics of disclosure: Communication Privacy Management in provider-patient conversations about sexual health.</ArticleTitle><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">SH25131</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1071/SH25131</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="BACKGROUND" NlmCategory="BACKGROUND">Conversations between physicians and patients about sexual health are influenced by interpersonal dynamics and social expectations, which shape how patients disclose sensitive information. The theory of Communication Privacy Management reveals inherent tensions and motivations for revealing and concealing private information, particularly in the context of broader cultural discourses.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">In-depth interviews with 20 female patients revealed how privacy management is shaped by broader discourses about clinical communication.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">Themes involve traditional dialectics of openness/closedness, conventionality/uniqueness, and emotional subjectivity/logical objectivity informed by cultural discourses around being a 'good' doctor or 'good' patient. Two novel dialectics are introduced. The first addresses 'their time/my time',&#xa0;which discusses the tension between valuing the patient's time and valuing the doctor's time. The second explores 'high power/low power' where patients discuss dilemmas around patients claiming their power.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSION" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">Theoretical advancements in Communication Privacy Management and practical implications for physician training are discussed.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>&#xa9; 2026 The Author(s) (or their employer(s)). Published by CSIRO Publishing.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Hernandez</LastName><ForeName>Rachael</ForeName><Initials>R</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0003-4919-5753</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Communication, University of Missouri, Switzler Hall, Columbia, MO, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Public Health, University of Missouri, Lewis Hall, Columbia, MO, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Ebersole</LastName><ForeName>Diana S</ForeName><Initials>DS</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Communication Studies, Kutztown University, 218 Rickenbach, Kutztown, PA 19530, USA. Email: ebersole@kutztown.edu.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>Australia</Country><MedlineTA>Sex Health</MedlineTA><NlmUniqueID>101242667</NlmUniqueID><ISSNLinking>1448-5028</ISSNLinking></MedlineJournalInfo><CitationSubset>IM</CitationSubset><MeshHeadingList><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D006801" MajorTopicYN="N">Humans</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D005260" MajorTopicYN="N">Female</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D010817" MajorTopicYN="Y">Physician-Patient Relations</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D000074384" MajorTopicYN="Y">Sexual Health</DescriptorName></Mes